    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1958-09-25T18:42:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1958-09-25T18:42:00-05:00" n="303"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d303">
                <head>303. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Department of State</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Embassy in Austria</gloss>
                    <note n="0" type="source" xml:id="d303fn0">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, 611.63/9–2558. Confidential. Drafted by <persName corresp="#p_CFL1"
                            >Chapin</persName>, cleared with Howe, and approved by <persName
                            corresp="#p_CTCJ1">Cameron</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1958-09-25T19:42:00-04:00">September 25, 1958, 7:42 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>919. Following based on uncleared memorandum conversation between Secretary and
                        <persName corresp="#p_FL1">Figl</persName> September 25.<note n="1"
                        xml:id="d303fn1">Foreign Minister <persName corresp="#p_FL1">Figl</persName>
                        was in Washington to meet with Secretary <persName corresp="#p_DJF1"
                            >Dulles</persName>, having arrived on September 24 from New York, where
                        he had been attending the 13th <gloss target="#t_UN1">U.N.</gloss> General
                        Assembly session since September 14. Two memoranda of conversation, on which
                        this telegram is based, are <hi rend="italic">ibid</hi>., Secretary’s
                        Memoranda of Conversation: Lot 64 D 199. A briefing memorandum for <persName
                            corresp="#p_FL1">Figl</persName>’s visit, September 24, from Elbrick to
                        the Secretary is <hi rend="italic">ibid</hi>., Central Files,
                        763.13/9–2458.</note>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_FL1">Figl</persName> cited progress on four topics which
                    Secretary raised with <persName corresp="#p_RJ1">Raab</persName> in May:
                    Austrian Assets Treaty, Vienna Memorandum negotiations, Article 26 negotiations,
                    and dollar liberalization. He hoped first three could be concluded by the end of
                    1958. Re liberalization he cited Cabinet action September 23 approving 5%
                    increase. Secretary requested <persName corresp="#p_FL1">Figl</persName> express
                    his gratification to Chancellor for progress.</p>
                <p>Following discussion Far East, <persName corresp="#p_FL1">Figl</persName> said
                    problem of concern to Austria which had struggled hard for freedom and still was
                    on frontier. Austria small country but wished contribute its bit to maintain
                    Free World. <persName corresp="#p_FL1">Figl</persName> had therefore announced
                    in <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> speech September 23 Austria ready
                    participate in permanent <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> Peace Force if
                    created. Had decided participation compatible with “military neutrality.”</p>
                <p>Secretary regretted Austria did not vote for Red China moratorium. <persName
                        corresp="#p_FL1">Figl</persName> stressed alignment with US on Hungary and
                    “all other issues in <gloss target="#t_GA1">GA</gloss>” but said could not go
                    along on moratorium.</p>
                <p>Elbrick meeting with <persName corresp="#p_FL1">Figl</persName>,
                        <persName>Fuchs</persName> September 26 re Austrian-US relations.<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d303fn2">See <ref target="#d304">Document 304</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_HCA1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Herter</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
